https://www.wolfram.com/mathematica/new-in-10/basic-and-formula-regions/curve-intersection.html.es here is a good example on how to plot the intersection. In a more simple case (following the example cited before you can plot the intersection of x^2] and x^3 with this code:
pts = Solve[x^2 == x^3, {x}];
graphs = Plot[{Sin[x], x^3}, {x, -5, 5}, PlotTheme -> "Detailed", 
   PlotRange -> Automatic];
intersections = 
  Graphics[{Red, PointSize[0.01], Point[{x, x^3} /. pts]}];
Show[graphs, intersections]

